3.1
Client-server architecture is a system where the client (like a browser or app) sends a request and the server processes it and sends back a response. The client mainly handles the user interface, while the server handles logic, data storage, and processing.
When I enter a URL in the browser, first it checks if the page is already in cache. If not, it does a DNS lookup to convert the domain name into an IP address. After getting the IP, the browser establishes a connection with the server using TCP, and if it is a secure website, SSL/TLS handshake also happens.
Then the browser sends an HTTP request (mostly GET request) to the server. The server processes it, may interact with a database, and sends back an HTTP response which contains HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. After that, the browser renders the page by building the DOM and displays it to the user.
To manage heavy traffic, we use techniques like load balancing, caching, and CDNs. Load balancing distributes traffic across multiple servers, caching reduces repeated work, and CDNs help deliver content faster from nearby locations.
There are two types of scaling:
Vertical scaling means increasing the power of a single server (more RAM, CPU).
Horizontal scaling means adding multiple servers and distributing the load between them.

