There are mainly two types of databases: SQL and NoSQL.
SQL databases are relational and store data in tables with rows and columns. Examples are PostgreSQL and MySQL. They are useful when data is structured and relationships are important.
NoSQL databases store data in flexible formats like JSON. Examples are MongoDB and Firebase. They are useful when data is unstructured or when high scalability is needed.
A SQL database consists of tables, rows, columns, indexes, and relationships using foreign keys.
SQL databases use B-Trees for indexing. B-Tree is a structure that keeps data sorted and helps in fast searching. Because of this, SELECT queries become faster.
But during heavy INSERT operations, having many indexes slows down performance. This is because every insert also needs to update all indexes.
When a B-Tree node becomes full, it splits into two nodes. This causes extra work like moving data, updating pointers, and writing changes to disk.
Physically on disk, this means more disk operations, rewriting of pages, and rebalancing of the tree. Because of this, write operations become slower when too many indexes are present.

3.4
Git is a version control system used to track changes in code.
Git merge and git rebase are used to combine changes from one branch to another. Git merge combines branches and creates a merge commit, keeping the full history. Git rebase rewrites history and makes it more linear and clean.
In Git, each commit is stored as an object which contains the snapshot of files, author details, timestamp, and the parent commit.
The commit hash is generated based on all this information.
When we do rebase, the parent commit changes. Even if the code is same, the parent reference is different. Because the hash depends on all the data including parent, the commit hash also changes.
So a commit is not just the data, it also depends on its position in the history.

